<TITLE> BNP pays tribute to Saifur </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 6 (bdnews24.com) The Bangladesh Nationalist Party has bid adieu to its veteran Saifur Rahman with floral tributes after he died on Saturday in a car crash. The body of the former finance minister was brought at the Naya Paltan headquaters of the main opposition party where his second namaj-e-janaza was held. Hundreds of political leaders from all parties and prominent people attended the janaza that began at around 12:40pm. Former president Abdur Rahman Biswas, BNP secretary general Khandaker Delwar Hossain, standing committee membesr Khandaker Mahbub Uddin Ahmed and Khandaker Mosharraf Hossain, vice president Altaf Hossain Chowdhury, joint secretary general Abdullah Al Noman, Mirza Abbas and Nazrul Islam Khan, BNP leader Mirza Fakhrul Islam, Rafiqul Islam Mian, Giasuddin Quader Chowdhury, Abdus Salam and Barkat Ullah Bulu, among others, were present. The first namaj-e-janaza of the veteran BNP leader was held at Gulshan Azad Mosque, attended by his family members and well wishers. Former president and BNP leader A Q M Badruddoza Chowdhury, Jatiya Party secretary general Ruhul Amin Hawlader, Sheikh Shahidul Islam and many high officials of the government attended the janaza. His third namaj-e-janaza was held at South Plaza of the parliament building at around 2:30pm. He will be buried at the family graveyard in Moulavibazar on Monday. Speaker Abdul Hamid, deputy speaker Shawkat Ali, former speaker Jamiruddin Sircar, finance minister A M A Muhith, chief whip Abdus Shahid, opposition chief whip Joynal Abdin Farrouque, MPs Salahuddin Quader Chowdhury, Tofail Ahmed, former finance adviser Mirza Azizul Islam, chief election commissioner ATM Shamsul Huda, Dhaka mayor Sadeque Hossain Khoka attended it. The speaker and the deputy speaker laid flowers on the coffin, while the chief whip offered flowers on behalf of parliament and the oppositon chief whip on behalf of the BNP chief. His Qulkhwani will be held at Gulshan Azad Mosque on Friday after Asr prayers. The BNP on Sunday started a three-day mourning programme to pay tribute, with party flag hoisted at half-mast and black flag at the party's central office in Naya Paltan. It has opened a condolence book for paying homage to the memory of the veteran leader at the party chairperson's Gulshan office. Foreign diplomats are scheduled to sign in the condolence book at around 5pm on Sunday and it will be open for common people from 10am to 5pm on Monday and Tuesday, office secretary Rizvi Ahmed told bdnews24.com. Chairperson Khaleda Zia discussed the funeral arrangements with the late politician's relatives at their Gulshan residence, Rizvi and chief whip Joynal Abdin Farrouque told reporters on Saturday night outside the family home in Dhaka. The late politician's eldest son, Naser Rahman, who went to Saudi Arabia to observe Umrah, reached Dhaka on Sunday morning. Family members earlier said the body would be buried at the family compound at Baharmordan in Moulavibazar district. Milad mahfils will be held to pray for the veteran leader at BNP offices across the country, Rizvi earlier told bdnews24.com. Saifur was declared dead at Brahmanbaria General Hospital on Saturday afternoon after his car crashed on the Dhaka-Sylhet highway. A police escort accompanied Rahman's remains to his Gulshan residence, where they arrived at 7:45pm on Saturday. bdnews2
